 "6.Be2 (the Classical / quiet line): White develops calmly and castles short. Your plan: ...e5, develop ...Be7 and "
 "...O-O, then ...b5 and queenside play. Calm versus calm - you are completely fine.",
 "6.Be3 (the English Attack, the critical modern test): White intends f3, Qd2, O-O-O and a pawn storm with g4-g5. "
 "Your plan: meet the race head on - ...e5, ...Be6, ...Nbd7, ...b5, ...Nb6 and push your own pawns at his king. "
 "Whoever's attack arrives first usually wins, so do not dawdle.",
 "6.Bg5 (the old main line): pins your knight and prepares Qf3 and O-O-O. Your sharpest reply is the famous "
 "...e6 and ...Nbd7 set-ups, including the razor-edged Poisoned Pawn (...Qb6 grabbing b2). Respect this one - it is "
 "theory-heavy, so this is the line to study from a dedicated source before you trust it.",
 "6.Bc4 (the Fischer-Sozin): White aims the bishop at f7. Neutralise it with ...e6 and timely ...b5, ...Bb7, and be "
 "ready for ...Nbd7-b6 to challenge the bishop.",
 "6.f3, 6.g3, 6.h3, 6.a4: side-lines and move-order tries. Develop sensibly, remember the standard plans (...e5 or "
 "...e6, queenside expansion, the ...d5 break when it frees you), and you will be fine.",
])
B.callout("The six things to actually know in the Najdorf",
    "1) The point of ...a6 is b5-control and queenside expansion. 2) Decide ...e5 or ...e6 deliberately. 3) If you "
    "play ...e5, watch the d5 hole forever. 4) Against the English Attack it is a race - generate your own ...b5 "
    "attack, do not just defend. 5) The freeing break is ...d5; when you achieve it safely you are usually equal or "
    "better. 6) Learn the Bg5 lines from a real source before trusting them - they are the sharpest.")
B.sec("Why this fixes your results")
B.para("Your Black problem is not that the Najdorf is hard; it is that you have been switching defences and so never "
    "built the pattern library that makes a defence work. Commit to this one. Play fifty training games as Black in "
    "it. Review each one by asking which plan you forgot. Within those fifty games your Black win rate will start to "
    "climb toward your White one, and the single largest gap in your chess will begin to close.")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 4 (Nimzo)
B.chapter(4,"Meeting 1.d4: The Nimzo-Indian","A principled answer, and a backup that connects to it.")
B.para("Against 1.d4 you already reach for the Nimzo-Indian, and it is an excellent choice for you - it is strategic but "
    "full of concrete bite, and it gives Black real winning chances rather than a passive equality. Let us make sure "
    "you understand WHY it works, and then plug the one hole every Nimzo player must plug.")
B.sec("The idea in one diagram")
B.para("1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Bb4. The bishop pins the c3-knight, and that knight is White's main defender of the e4 "
    "square. So the Nimzo is, at heart, a fight for e4 and for the centre.")
B.board("rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/4pn2/8/1bPP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 4 4",
        "The Nimzo-Indian after 3...Bb4. The bishop pins the knight that guards e4.",
        moveline="1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Bb4")
B.para("The defining strategic transaction is this: very often you will play ...Bxc3, giving up your bishop for the "
    "knight. In return White's pawns are doubled on the c-file (pawns on c3 and c4). Now the game becomes a clash of "
    "two philosophies - White has the bishop pair and open lines and wants the position to open up; you have the "
    "superior pawn structure and want to blockade the doubled pawns, fix them as weaknesses, and keep the position "
    "controlled. Knowing which side of that bargain you are on tells you how to play every resulting middlegame: "
    "when you have given up the bishop, you keep things closed and target c4; when White cannot make the bishops "
    "work, your structure wins the long game.")
B.sec("White's main set-ups")
B.bullets([
 "4.e3 (the Rubinstein, by far the most common): solid and flexible. Develop with ...O-O, ...d5 or ...c5 striking "
 "the centre, and decide on ...Bxc3 based on whether White has committed pieces awkwardly.",
 "4.Qc2 (the Classical): White avoids the doubled pawns by recapturing on c3 with the queen. Here ...d5 and ...c5 "
 "are thematic, and the bishop pair is contested on equal terms.",
 "4.f3 and 4.Nf3 and 4.g3: each has its own flavour, but in all of them your anchors are the same - fight for e4 "
 "and the centre, complete development, and use the ...c5 and ...d5 breaks.",
])
B.sec("The hole every Nimzo player must plug")
B.para("Here is the catch that probably contributes to your Black results: White does not have to allow the Nimzo. "
    "After 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6, White can play 3.Nf3 instead of 3.Nc3, and now there is no knight on c3 to pin - your "
    "Nimzo never appears. If you do not have a prepared answer, you are improvising from move three, which is exactly "
    "the kind of unsettled position that costs you games.")
B.callout("Your backup: the Ragozin",
    "Against 3.Nf3 play 3...d5, and after 4.Nc3 you get 4...Bb4 anyway - this is the Ragozin, and it transposes back "
    "into Nimzo-like positions with the bishop doing its familiar job. Learning the Nimzo and the Ragozin together "
    "gives you ONE connected system against everything 1.d4 can try. This pairing - Nimzo plus Ragozin - is the "
    "single most efficient 1.d4 repertoire for a player of your level.")
B.para("With the Najdorf against 1.e4 and the Nimzo-Ragozin against 1.d4, you now have a complete, principled, "
    "connected set of Black openings. No more improvising on move three. That structural certainty, more than any "
    "single variation, is what will lift your Black results.")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 5 (White)
B.chapter(5,"With White: Sharpening Your 1.e4","You are already good here. Let us make you ruthless.")
B.para("Your White results are already your strength, so this chapter is about consolidation, not reinvention. The aim "
    "is to remove the few soft spots and to make sure your preparation time flows toward your weaknesses rather than "
    "toward learning yet another opening.")
B.sec("Against the Sicilian: commit to the Open")
B.para("You play the Open Sicilian (2.Nf3 followed by 3.d4) but inconsistently. Commit to it. The Open Sicilian is the "
    "most challenging try against the Sicilian and - crucially for you - the positions resemble the ones you defend "
    "as a Najdorf player, so every hour you spend understanding Sicilian structures pays off on BOTH sides of the "
    "board. That double-dividend is the most efficient study you can do. Pick your set-up against each Black system "
    "(a main line or a respected Anti-line you trust) and play it every time until the middlegames are automatic.")
B.sec("Against 1...e5: the Italian now, the Ruy Lopez next")
B.para("Keep the Italian Game as your everyday weapon - it leads to rich middlegames and you handle them well. In "
    "parallel, begin learning the Ruy Lopez. It is the deepest, most instructive 1.e4 e5 opening in chess, and "
    "studying it will teach you more about classical strategy - the slow build-up, the d4 break, manoeuvring the "
    "knight to g3 or f5 - than any other single opening. You do not have to switch overnight; let the Ruy grow "
    "alongside the Italian and adopt it when you trust it.")
B.sec("Against the French and Caro-Kann: tidy, not heavy")
B.bullets([
 "French: the Tarrasch (3.Nd2) gives you clean, understandable structures without the theory load of the main "
 "lines. Your plan is usually central control and a kingside initiative; learn the typical isolated-queen-pawn and "
 "advance structures that arise.",
 "Caro-Kann: the Advance Variation (3.e5) grabs space and steers the game into structures where your space advantage "
 "and kingside chances do the talking. Learn how to handle Black's ...Bf5 and the ...c5 break against your centre.",
])
B.callout("The White principle that matters most for you",
    "Your White openings should buy you a sound, slightly more active middlegame - and then your tactical strength "
    "does the rest. Do not chase a forced refutation out of the opening. Get a good position, keep your king safe "
    "(yes, even with White), and let your calculation win the game.")

# =================================================================== PART III
B.part("PART III","The Skills That Win Games")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 6 (Calculation)
B.chapter(6,"Calculation Under the Clock","Closing the gap between knowing and seeing.")
B.para("Your blitz rating is roughly five hundred points below your rapid. Read that correctly: it is good news. It "
    "means the chess knowledge is already there - when you are given time, you reach 2000-level decisions - and what "
    "is missing is SPEED, which is the most trainable thing in chess. This chapter gives you a method for calculating "
    "accurately, and a drill for making that method fast.")
B.sec("A method you can repeat in every position")
B.numbered([
 "Look at all forcing moves first - every check, every capture, every direct threat, for BOTH sides. Forcing moves "
 "narrow the tree and they are where tactics live. Most missed combinations are missed because the player never "
 "listed the move, not because they miscalculated it.",
 "Pick your candidate moves - usually two or three serious ones. Do not calculate the first move that catches your "
 "eye; name the candidates, then choose what to calculate.",
 "Calculate each candidate as a clean line, one move at a time, all the way to a position that is quiet enough to "
 "judge. Do not stop in the middle of a sequence and guess.",
 "Evaluate the position at the end of the line - is it good for you? Then compare your candidates and choose.",
 "Before you play it, run the blunder-check: 'If I play this, what is my opponent's most forcing reply?' This single "
 "question, asked every move, will erase most of your one-move oversights - the kind that cost you blitz games.",
])
B.callout("The discipline that wins time scrambles",
    "In every game, the moment your position sharpens, silently say the three words: checks, captures, threats. "
    "Train it until it is a reflex. Players who do this do not 'see more' than you - they simply look in the right "
    "order, so they find the same ideas in a third of the time. That is your entire blitz gap in one habit.")
B.sec("The drill that builds speed: the Woodpecker idea")
B.para("Here is the most effective calculation drill known, and it is simple. Take a set of tactical puzzles - say a "
    "few hundred - and solve the whole set. Note how long it took. Then solve the SAME set again. And again, each "
    "time faster. The positions do not change, so you are not learning new tactics; you are burning the patterns so "
    "deep that you recognise them instantly. After several cycles, motifs that used to take you thirty seconds "
    "appear in one. This is precisely the training that converts your rapid strength into blitz strength, and it is "
    "the single highest-value thing you can do for your calculation.")
B.sec("Clock discipline")
B.bullets([
 "Set a soft cap: in a rapid game, almost never spend more than three minutes on one move. If you are over it, you "
 "are usually choosing between moves that are close anyway - pick the principled one and move.",
 "Spend your time at the RIGHT moments: when the position changes character (a trade, a pawn break, the start of an "
 "attack). Do not burn clock in quiet positions where almost any sensible move keeps the balance.",
 "When low on time, do not try to calculate deeply - SIMPLIFY. Trade into a position you understand, or steer for an "
 "endgame structure you know. A clear plan beats a deep calculation you do not have time to finish.",
])

# ---------------- CHAPTER 7 (King safety)
B.chapter(7,"King Safety: Learning to Hold","The chapter your losses have been asking for.")
B.para("This is the chapter that will save you the most games, because the failure it describes is the one that recurs "
    "most often in your defeats. You get a fine position. Your opponent starts an attack on your king. You keep "
    "playing on the other side of the board, or you defend one move too late, and then it is over. The cause is not "
    "weak calculation - you have shown you can calculate. The cause is that you under-RESPECT the attack because you "
    "are wired to be the attacker. We are going to rewire that.")
B.sec("Rule one: count the attackers and the defenders")
B.para("Before you allow or ignore an enemy build-up near your king, literally count. How many of your opponent's "
    "pieces can reach the squares around your king? How many of yours defend them? If attackers outnumber defenders, "
    "you are in danger NOW, regardless of the material count or how nice your queenside looks. The most common "
    "version of your loss is that the attackers quietly reached three while your defenders stayed at one, and you "
    "noticed on the move it became mate. Count early, and count often.")
B.sec("Rule two: choose your castling side with the pawns in mind")
B.bullets([
 "If your opponent's pieces and pawns point at one wing, castle the OTHER way if you reasonably can.",
 "Opposite-side castling means both sides race with pawn storms - this is a calculation and tempo race, and it "
 "suits your style, but you must play it as a race: push your attack with energy AND watch the clock on theirs.",
 "Same-side castling means king safety is about piece placement and the pawn shield - do not casually push the "
 "pawns in front of your own king (f, g, h) without a concrete reason; every such push is a hook for the enemy.",
])
B.sec("Rule three: the three ways to defend, in order of preference")
B.numbered([
 "Remove the attacker. The cleanest defence is to trade off your opponent's most dangerous attacking piece - "
 "especially a light-squared bishop aiming at your king, or an attacking knight. One well-timed trade can end an "
 "attack before it starts.",
 "Give material back. If you are ahead - or even if you are not - returning a pawn or the exchange to blunt the "
 "attack and reach a safe position is often the best practical decision. Attackers like you hate doing this; learn "
 "to love it. A safe king up nothing beats a shaky king up a pawn.",
 "Walk the king or block. Sometimes the king is safest taking a quiet step (...Kh8, ...Kg7 after the storm) or you "
 "interpose a piece and consolidate. The art is to find the move after which the attack simply has no follow-up.",
])
B.sec("Recognise the patterns that are coming for you")
B.para("Two attacking schemes appear constantly against a kingside-castled player, and you should know them so well "
    "that you feel them forming.")
B.bullets([
 "The Greek Gift sacrifice: a bishop takes on h7 (Bxh7+), the king is dragged out with ...Kxh7, a knight jumps to "
 "g5 with check, and the queen swings to h5 with a mating attack. The warning signs are an enemy bishop aiming at "
 "h7, a knight ready to reach g5, and queen access to the h-file. When you see those three ingredients, do not "
 "allow the position to mature - trade the bishop, or cover g5 and h7 in advance.",
 "The pawn storm: against opposite-side castling, enemy pawns (g and h, or b and a) march at your king to rip open "
 "a file. The defence is to slow the storm (a timely pawn block that forces the storm to spend extra moves) and to "
 "make sure YOUR storm arrives first or your centre breaks open before his rooks land.",
])
B.callout("The mindset shift that fixes king safety",
    "You are an attacker, so train yourself to ask, on the opponent's behalf, the attacker's question: 'If I were "
    "playing this position from the other side, how would I get at my king?' You already think this way when YOU "
    "attack. Turn that same imagination around to defend, and the attacks that used to surprise you will start "
    "announcing themselves three moves early.")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 8 (Middlegame)
B.chapter(8,"The Middlegame Bridge","What to do when there is no tactic yet.")
B.para("The opening is over. There is no combination on the board. This is the moment you sometimes drift - and it is "
    "the moment that separates a 2000 from a master. The master does not need a tactic here; the master makes a "
    "PLAN, improves the position by small degrees, and waits for the tactic to be created by the pressure. This "
    "chapter teaches you how to find that plan.")
B.sec("How to find a plan in any quiet position")
B.numbered([
 "Read the pawn structure. The pawns define the terrain - which files are open, which squares are weak, where each "
 "side should attack. Almost every correct plan is written in the pawn structure if you know how to read it.",
 "Find the weaknesses - yours and your opponent's. A weak square (one no pawn can defend), a backward or isolated "
 "pawn, a hole in front of a king. Your plan is usually 'attack his weakness' or 'fix and blockade it.'",
 "Find your worst piece and improve it. A famous rule: the quality of your position is often set by your LEAST "
 "active piece. If you have nothing forcing to do, the best move is frequently to reroute your worst-placed piece "
 "to a better square. Quiet positions are won by accumulating these small improvements.",
 "Identify the pawn break. Plans are powered by pawn breaks - the move that opens a file or frees your pieces. Know "
 "the thematic break for your structure and prepare it.",
])
B.sec("The structures you actually reach - and their plans")
B.para("Because your repertoire is fixed now, you reach a small, predictable set of structures. Learn these four and you "
    "will understand the majority of your own middlegames.")
B.bullets([
 "The Najdorf / Scheveningen structures (from your Black games and your White Open Sicilians): play on opposite "
 "wings, race the attacks, and remember the freeing ...d5 break for Black and the f-file / kingside play for White.",
 "The Isolated Queen's Pawn (IQP): the side with the isolated pawn plays for activity, the d5 outpost, and a "
 "kingside attack BEFORE the pawn becomes weak; the side against it blockades the pawn on the square in front of "
 "it, trades pieces, and aims for an endgame where the pawn falls. Know which side you are - the plans are "
 "opposite.",
 "The Maroczy Bind: a big white pawn centre on c4 and e4 squeezes Black; White improves slowly and expands, Black "
 "seeks the freeing ...b5 or ...d5 break and piece activity.",
 "The Nimzo doubled-pawn structures: the side with the doubled c-pawns wants open lines and the bishop pair to "
 "work; the other side blockades, fixes the pawns as targets, and grinds.",
])
B.sec("Prophylaxis - the habit that lifts you to master")
B.para("Prophylaxis is the single most important thinking habit above 2000, and it is just one question asked every "
    "move: 'What does my opponent want to do?' Find his plan, his break, his best piece manoeuvre - and then ask "
    "whether you can prevent it before you pursue your own. Most players think only about their own ideas; the "
    "player who also stops yours will slowly strangle you. Build this question into your move routine and you will "
    "feel your quiet positions stop drifting.")
B.callout("Your anti-drift checklist",
    "When there is no tactic and you do not know what to do, run this in order: 1) What's the pawn structure telling "
    "me? 2) Where are the weak squares and pawns? 3) What's my worst piece, and can I improve it? 4) What's my "
    "opponent's plan, and can I stop it? You will almost always find a useful move before you reach the end.")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 9 (Attacking)
B.chapter(9,"Attacking the Right Way","Refining the weapon you already have.")
B.para("This is the one chapter that builds on a strength rather than repairing a weakness. You already love to attack; "
    "the goal here is to make your attacks SOUND, so that they win against strong defenders rather than only against "
    "weak ones - and so that you stop confusing a real attack with a hopeful one.")
B.sec("The preconditions for a sound attack")
B.bullets([
 "A target - usually the enemy king, but it can be a weakness. No target, no attack; what you have instead is a "
 "lunge that weakens your own position.",
 "More force at the point of contact than the defender has. This is just the counting rule from Chapter 7, run in "
 "the other direction: attack where YOUR attackers outnumber his defenders.",
 "Open or opening lines. Attacks travel down open files and diagonals. If everything is closed, the right "
 "preparation is a pawn break to open a road for your pieces, not a premature sacrifice.",
 "Your own king is safe enough to commit. The most common cause of a failed attack at your level is that the "
 "attacker's OWN king was loose, so the defender's counterattack arrived first. Secure your king, then attack.",
])
B.sec("Sound sacrifice versus hope")
B.para("A sacrifice is sound when you can either calculate a concrete forced sequence to the win, or you get a clear, "
    "lasting compensation you can name - a permanently exposed king, a winning attack with more attackers than "
    "defenders, two pawns and the initiative. A sacrifice is hope when your honest answer to 'and if he just "
    "defends accurately?' is 'then I am probably worse, but maybe he'll go wrong.' Against weak opposition hope "
    "works and reinforces a bad habit; against strong opposition it loses. Train yourself to tell the difference by "
    "always asking the defender's-best-reply question before you commit material.")
B.callout("The attacker's checklist",
    "Before you launch: Do I have a target? Do I have more attackers than he has defenders there? Are the lines open "
    "or can I open them? Is my own king safe? If a sacrifice - can I calculate it to a win, or name concrete "
    "compensation? Four yeses and a clear answer to the last: attack with full force. A no: improve the position "
    "first, the way Chapter 8 teaches, and let the attack mature.")

# =================================================================== PART IV
B.part("PART IV","The Endgame & The Long Game")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 10 (Endgames)
B.chapter(10,"Endgames You Will Actually Reach","The phase you avoid, turned into a weapon.")
B.para("Most improving attackers neglect endgames because their games rarely reach them - but that is backwards. They "
    "rarely reach endgames PARTLY because they steer away from positions they do not trust. Learn a handful of exact "
    "endgames and two things happen: you win the ones you reach, and you become willing to trade into a winning "
    "endgame instead of forcing a murky attack. Here is the minimum that pays the maximum.")
B.sec("The opposition - the key to all king-and-pawn endings")
B.para("When the two kings face each other with one square between them and it is NOT your move, you 'have the "
    "opposition' - your opponent must give way. This tiny rule decides whether a king-and-pawn ending is won or "
    "drawn, because the side with the opposition can force the enemy king to step aside and let his own king (and "
    "pawn) advance to the key squares.")
B.board({"e5":"K","e7":"k"},
        "Direct opposition. Kings face off with one square between them; the side NOT to move controls the squares ahead.",
        shaded={"d6","e6","f6"})
B.para("In the diagram, whoever is to move must give ground - if White is to move, the black king holds him back along "
    "the shaded squares; if Black is to move, White's king breaks through. Drilling this until it is automatic is "
    "the foundation of every pawn ending, and pawn endings decide a surprising number of games.")
B.sec("The rule of the square - can the king catch the pawn?")
B.para("When a lone passed pawn runs for promotion and the enemy king tries to catch it, you do not have to calculate "
    "move by move. Draw an imaginary square whose side equals the distance from the pawn to its promotion square. If "
    "the defending king stands inside that square - or can step into it on its move - it catches the pawn. If not, "
    "the pawn queens. Learn to see the square instantly.")
B.board({"h5":"P","e5":"k","a1":"K"},
        "Rule of the square. The pawn's square is shaded; the black king is on its edge and so catches the pawn (with Black to move).",
        shaded={"e5","f5","g5","h5","e6","f6","g6","h6","e7","f7","g7","h7","e8","f8","g8","h8"})
B.para("Here the h-pawn must travel from h5 to h8. The shaded region is its square; because the black king on e5 stands "
    "on the edge of that square and it is Black to move, the king steps in and stops the pawn. Move the king one "
    "file further away - off the square - and the pawn would promote untouched.")
B.sec("Rook endings - where most endgames actually live")
B.para("Rook endings are the most common endgame in practical chess, so a little knowledge here is worth a great deal. "
    "Three principles carry you most of the way:")
B.numbered([
 "Activity beats material. An active rook - behind a passed pawn, or cutting off the enemy king - is often worth a "
 "pawn or more. Do not grovel to defend a pawn with a passive rook; seek activity.",
 "Put your rook BEHIND passed pawns - yours or your opponent's (the Tarrasch rule). Behind your own passer it "
 "supports the advance; behind the enemy's it restrains it while your king comes to help.",
 "Know the two reference positions. The LUCENA position (you are a pawn up, your pawn on the 7th, your king in "
 "front) is the winning technique - you 'build a bridge' with your rook to shelter your king from checks while the "
 "pawn promotes. The PHILIDOR position (you are defending) is the drawing technique - keep your rook on your third "
 "rank to deny the enemy king entry, and once the pawn advances to give it a target, switch to checking from "
 "behind. Memorise these two by name and method; they decide countless games.",
])
B.callout("Your endgame priority list",
    "Study in this order, because this is the order they decide your games: 1) the opposition and basic king-and-pawn "
    "wins/draws; 2) the rule of the square; 3) rook activity and rook-behind-passers; 4) the Lucena and Philidor "
    "positions by heart; 5) basic queen-versus-pawn. That short list, truly mastered, outperforms a thick endgame "
    "encyclopaedia you only skim.")

# ---------------- CHAPTER 11 (Training)
B.chapter(11,"How to Train From Here","Turning all of this into rating points.")
B.para("A book is potential; a routine is results. This final chapter turns everything above into a way of working you "
    "can sustain. None of it requires more than a couple of focused hours on a weekday.")
B.sec("Analyse your own games - the right way")
B.para("This is the highest-value habit in all of chess improvement, and almost everyone does it wrong by switching on "
    "the engine immediately. Do it in two passes. FIRST, with the engine off, play through your game and write your "
    "honest thoughts: where you were unsure, what you were planning, the move you now think was the mistake and WHY. "
    "This trains your judgement - the thing that actually plays your games. THEN turn the engine on to check your "
    "conclusions. The engine tells you WHAT; only your own first pass teaches you to see it next time.")
B.sec("A weekly rhythm")
B.bullets([
 "Daily warm-up: thirty tactics puzzles, fast. Pattern maintenance.",
 "Three days a week: a calculation set (the Woodpecker drill) plus repertoire review of your Najdorf, Nimzo, or "
 "1.e4 lines - one structure at a time, plans first.",
 "Two days a week: an endgame session from the priority list, and a positional session - study one of your four "
 "structures or one master game played slowly.",
 "Weekend: three to five serious rapid games at 15+10, each one analysed by the two-pass method above. Quality over "
 "quantity; one deeply reviewed game teaches more than ten unexamined ones.",
 "Monthly: review your recent losses as a batch and write the recurring sentence. Adjust what you train next month "
 "to attack it.",
])
B.sec("On plateaus and patience")
B.para("You will plateau. Everyone does, and the plateau before a breakthrough feels exactly like the plateau before "
    "quitting - the difference is only what you do next. When the rating stalls, do not thrash between openings or "
    "chase a magic resource. Return to this book's diagnosis, pick the weakness that is still costing you the most, "
    "and train it specifically for a month. Improvement at your level is not linear; it comes in steps, after the "
    "work and not during it. Trust the process you can see working in your own analysis, even when the number on the "
    "screen has not moved yet.")
B.sec("Over the board")
B.para("Finally: play real chess, against real people, across a real board. Online rapid is excellent training, but the "
    "skills this book teaches - holding under pressure, defending calmly, grinding an endgame - are tested most "
    "honestly in classical over-the-board play. Find a club. Enter a tournament. Expect your first rated results to "
    "feel modest; that is the normal tax everyone pays moving from the screen to the board, and it says nothing "
    "about your ceiling. The player who learns to hold, and who plays where it counts, goes a very long way.")
B.quote("Attackers learn to attack by losing. They become great by learning to hold. You have done the first half. "
        "This book is the second.","")

# =================================================================== APPENDICES
B.part("APPENDICES","Tools For The Road")

# Appendix A - cheat sheet
B.chapter("A","The One-Page Laws","Pin these to the wall above your board.")
B.sec("Opening")
B.bullets([
 "Know your openings by PLANS, not moves.",
 "One main answer to each first move - depth over breadth.",
